# ECM Analyst (Boutique Corporate Advisory)

## Overview
ECM analysts at boutique advisory firms advise companies on raising equity capital through IPOs, secondary offerings, and block trades, combining financial analysis, market assessment, transaction execution, and client advisory work.

## Core Responsibilities
- Supporting IPO and secondary offering transactions from pitch through execution and settlement, coordinating across company management, lawyers, accountants, underwriters, and regulators
- Building detailed financial models and performing valuations using DCF, comparable companies, and precedent transaction methodologies to advise companies on pricing and structure
- Analyzing public market conditions, investor appetite, comparable transactions, and optimal timing to advise on market windows and deal positioning strategies
- Coordinating financial, legal, and operational due diligence across advisors and participating in formal due diligence committee meetings to identify and document risks
- Drafting and reviewing prospectuses, offer documents, investor presentations ensuring accuracy, completeness, and compliance with ASX and ASIC regulatory requirements
- Preparing companies for investor roadshows by coordinating meetings, developing Q&A materials, and managing information flow between management teams and institutional investors

## Key Skills Required

### Technical Skills
- Advanced Excel modeling (three-statement models, DCF, sensitivity analysis, cap tables)
- PowerPoint proficiency for professional pitch decks and investor materials
- Financial statement analysis and valuation methodologies (trading/transaction comps)
- Understanding ASX listing requirements, ASIC regulations, and Corporations Act provisions

### Interpersonal Skills
- Exceptional attention to detail (prospectus errors carry serious legal consequences)
- Time management under intense deadline pressure during live transactions
- Clear written/verbal communication with senior clients (CEOs, CFOs, Boards)
- Resilience and ability to work long hours (60-80/week) during transactions

### Regulatory Knowledge
- ASX Listing Rules (admission requirements, continuous disclosure, capital raising)
- ASIC Regulatory Guides (especially RG 228 on prospectuses)
- Corporations Act fundraising and disclosure provisions
- Awareness of takeover regulations and substantial holder requirements

## Work Mode

### Analytical Work (55-65%)
Excel financial modeling, DCF and comparable company valuations, market research on recent IPOs and equity raisings, drafting prospectus sections and investor presentations, sensitivity analyses showing dilution and pro-forma metrics.

### Meetings & Coordination (20-25%)
Client meetings with management teams, due diligence sessions with lawyers and accountants, due diligence committee meetings documenting transaction risks, internal team discussions on deal strategy and execution milestones.

### Project Management (10-15%)
Timeline tracking for prospectus lodgement and roadshow milestones, action item follow-up across external advisors, data room coordination, document version control, managing information flow between multiple parties.

### Administrative Tasks (5-10%)
Formatting investor presentations, printing and binding deal documents, organizing roadshow travel arrangements, file organization and archiving, preparing board materials and management presentations for client meetings.

### Client Support (5-10%)
Attending client presentations (primarily listening/note-taking early career), coordinating meeting logistics, conducting background research on prospective clients, supporting senior team members on pitches for new mandates.

## Workplace Culture
Small teams (3-10 people) at boutique firms working on 2-5 active transactions simultaneously in intensely deadline-driven environment with long hours but high-caliber learning and direct exposure.

